Zen Browser Docker Deployment
Guide1. Environment Verification & PreparationBefore deploying, ensure your host environment (Debian/RHEL/WSL2) is ready to handle GUI-based containers.
Check Docker Service StatusVerify that the Docker daemon is active and running:Bash# Check status
sudo systemctl status docker

# Start if inactive
sudo systemctl start docker

Identify Host User Permissions (PUID/PGID)To avoid permission conflicts between the host and the container, you must identify your user's unique IDs. 
Run the following command:Bashid
PUID: Your user ID (typically 1000).PGID: Your group ID (typically 1000).
2. Persistent Storage InitializationDocker containers are ephemeral by default. To ensure your browser profile, history, and bookmarks persist through container updates or restarts, initialize a dedicated configuration directory.
Bash# Create a dedicated directory for Zen configuration
mkdir -p ~/zen-config

3. Image Acquisition (Pulling)
Download the official Zen Browser image layers from the LinuxServer.io registry.
Bashdocker pull lscr.io/linuxserver/zen:latest

# 4. Full Deployment Command
The following command initializes the container with standard GUI configurations, port mappings, and necessary security overrides.Bashdocker run -d \
  --name=zen-browser \
  --security-opt seccomp=unconfined \
  -e PUID=1000 \
  -e PGID=1000 \
  -e TZ=Etc/UTC \
  -p 3000:3000 \
  -p 3001:3001 \
  -v ~/zen-config:/config \
  --shm-size="1gb" \
  --restart unless-stopped \
  lscr.io/linuxserver/zen:latest

## Detailed Flag Documentation


-dDetached Mode: Runs the container in the background.
--security-optSeccomp: unconfined is often required for Chromium-based sandboxing to function inside Docker.
-p 3000:3000HTTP GUI: Maps the web-based interface to your host port 3000.
-v ~/zen-config:/configVolume Mapping: Bridges your local directory to the container's internal settings for data persistence.
--shm-size="1gb"Shared Memory: Prevents browser tab crashes by allocating sufficient memory for rendering.
--restart unless-stoppedPolicy: Automatically restarts the container on host reboot unless manually stopped.

# 5. Verification & Final AccessAfter execution, verify the container's operational status and access the browser.Container Audit: Run docker ps to verify the container is "Up".Web Access: Open your local browser and navigate to:http://localhost:3000Result: 
You will now see the Zen Browser GUI running inside your browser via KasmVNC.
